SIMPLE: muniment
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muniment
<hw>Mu"ni*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>munimentum</ets>, fr. <ets>munire</ets> to fortify. See
<er>Munition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of supporting or
defending.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which supports or defends; stronghold; place or
means of defense; munition; assistance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Other
<xex>muniments</xex> and petty helps.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A record; the evidences or writings
whereby a man is enabled to defend the title to his estate; title deeds
and papers.</def> <rj><au>Blount.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Muniment room</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Muniment house</b></col></mcol>, <cd>that room in a cathedral,
castle, or other public building, which is used for keeping the records,
charters, seals, deeds, and the like.</cd> <au>Gwilt.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munite</ent>⟦br⟧
